text: Hydrothermal fluid is a type of leachate defined as high-temperature water ejected from hydrothermal vents, laden with dissolved metals and minerals as a result of percolation through crustal rocks.
Nitrate reducing sediment, defined as sediment hosting and characterized by active nitrate reducing microbial communities, is a type of anaerobic sediment.

Drop stone is a type of piece of rock and also a type of something that is at least part of some submerged bed. It is defined as a piece of rock which fell vertically through the water column into finer-grained water-deposited sedimentary rocks. Drop stone has an exact synonym, dropstone.

Organic matter fall is a type of mass of biological material that is at least located in, surrounded by, or adjacent to some water body, specifically liquid water or a submerged bed. It is defined as an accumulation of organic matter that has fallen to the bottom of a body of water.
Plant matter fall, which is a type of organic matter fall, is defined as the accumulation of plant matter that has fallen to the bottom of a body of water.

An animal carcass fall is a type of carcass defined as the carcass of an animal that has fallen to the bottom of a body of water. This entity not only is located in some water body but also is surrounded by liquid water and is adjacent to a submerged bed.

Whale fall is a type of animal carcass fall and is defined as the term used for a whale carcass that has fallen to the ocean floor. When a whale dies in shallow water, its carcass is typically devoured by scavengers over a relatively short period, within several months. However, in deeper water, at depths of 2,000 m (6,600 ft) or greater, fewer scavenger species exist. As a result, the carcass can provide sustenance for a complex localized ecosystem over periods of decades.
Seal fall is a type of animal carcass fall, defined as the term used for a seal carcass that has fallen to the ocean floor.
A wood fall is a type of plant matter fall and is defined as an accumulation of woody plant material that has fallen to the ocean floor.

A marine reef is the same as an entity that intersects with both a reef and something that is at least located in some marine water body. It is a type of reef as well as a type of entity that is at least located in some marine water body. Furthermore, a marine reef is defined as a reef which is located in a marine water body.
The marine coral reef flat zone is a type of marine reef and is also a type of structure that constitutes at least part of some coral reefs.
The marine coral reef back reef is a type of marine reef and is considered a part of some coral reefs.
A marine coral reef crest is a type of marine reef and is considered to be at least part of some coral reefs.
The marine coral reef fore reef is a type of marine reef and also a type of structure that constitutes at least part of some coral reefs.
The marine coral reef buttress zone is a type of marine reef, which is also considered as a part of some coral reefs.
Marine coral reef deep fore reef is a type of marine reef, and it is also a type of entity that constitutes at least part of some coral reef.
A marine subtidal rocky reef is both a type of rocky reef and a type of marine reef. It is defined as a rocky reef located in the subtidal zone of a marine water body.
Manganese reducing sediment is a type of anaerobic sediment that is defined as a sediment hosting and characterized by active manganese-reducing microbial communities.
Iron reducing sediment is a type of anaerobic sediment defined as sediment hosting and characterized by active iron-reducing microbial communities.
Sulphate reducing sediment, which is a type of anaerobic sediment, is defined as sediment that hosts and is characterized by active sulphate reducing microbial communities.
Carbon dioxide reducing sediment is a type of anaerobic sediment, which is defined as sediment that hosts and is characterized by active carbon dioxide reducing microbial communities.

Organic material is equivalent to something that is both an environmental material and something that is composed primarily of biomacromolecules. It is classified as a type of environmental material and also as a type that is composed primarily of biomacromolecules. Organic material is defined as environmental material derived from living organisms and primarily composed of one or more biomacromolecules. Additionally, organic material is precisely synonymous with biomass.

Biofilm material is categorized as an organic material. It is defined as material derived from a biofilm, which is an aggregate of microorganisms where cells stick to each other and/or to a surface. The cells within biofilms are often encased within a self-produced matrix known as extracellular polymeric substance (EPS). This biofilm EPS, also called slime, is a polymeric mixture primarily made up of extracellular DNA, proteins, and polysaccharides arranged in different configurations.

Microbial mat material is the same as something that intersects between organic material and something that at least derives from some microbial mat. It is a type of organic material and also a type of something that at least derives from some microbial mat. Additionally, microbial mat material is defined as material derived from a microbial mat, which is a multi-layered sheet of micro-organisms, primarily bacteria and archaea, creating a wide range of internal chemical environments.

Marine snow is a type of detritus characterized by being a continuous shower of mostly organic detritus falling from the upper layers of the water column. Its origin is rooted in activities within the productive photic zone.

A marine pockmark is a type of crater defined as pockmarks being craters in the seabed resulting from the release of gas or liquid. They are generally formed in soft, fine-grained seabed sediments by the escape of fluids, such as gas or water but mainly methane, into the water column.

A marine sponge reef is a type of marine reef that is primarily built by marine sponges. The primary frame-building sponges that contribute to these reefs are all members of the order Hexactinosa. These reefs are exclusively found in glacier-scoured troughs located on the low-angle continental shelf, where the seafloor is stable and consists of rock, coarse gravel, and large boulders.
An organ is a type of organic object that is defined as a collection of tissues joined in a structural unit to serve a common function.

A photophore is an organ that is defined as a light-emitting organ appearing as luminous spots on various marine animals, including fish and cephalopods. This organ ranges in complexity from simple structures to ones as intricate as the human eye, featuring lenses, shutters, color filters, and reflectors. The light emission can originate from different sources; it can be produced through the digestion of prey, from specialized mitochondrial cells known as photocytes ("light producing" cells), or from symbiotic bacteria associated with the organism.
A root nodule is a type of organ with the definition that it occurs on the roots of plants that associate with symbiotic nitrogen-fixing bacteria.

The trophosome is a type of organ with a definition that specifies it as a specialised organ found in deep-sea tube worms inhabiting hydrothermal vent environments. It is colonized by chemosynthetic bacteria which supply the host worm with organic compounds. This term may also be applied to similar organs in other worms.

Mycetome is a type of organ defined as a specialized organ that is connected to the gut in beetles, hosting a symbiotic yeast. This yeast assists in the digestion of less nutritious foods, supplies needed B-vitamins and sterols, and provides resistance to certain toxins.

A determinate root nodule is a type of root nodule defined as those found on tropical (sub)legumes, such as those of the genera Glycine (soybean), Phaseolus (common bean), Lotus, and Vigna. These determinate nodules lose meristematic activity shortly after initiation, with growth being attributed to cell expansion, resulting in mature nodules that are spherical in shape.

An indeterminate root nodule is a type of root nodule characterized by its presence on temperate legumes such as Pisum (pea), Medicago (alfalfa), Trifolium (clover), and Vicia (vetch). The defining feature of indeterminate nodules is their active apical meristem, which continuously produces new cells for growth throughout the nodule's lifespan. This unique characteristic has led to them being termed "indeterminate." Additionally, the ongoing growth of indeterminate nodules results in the formation of zones that distinguish various stages of development and symbiosis.

Indeterminate root nodule active meristem is a type of indeterminate root nodule, and it is also a type of something that constitutes at least part of some indeterminate root nodule. It is defined as a part of an indeterminate root nodule where new nodule tissue is formed, which will later differentiate into the other zones of the nodule.

The indeterminate root nodule infection zone is a type of indeterminate root nodule and also falls under the category of something that is at least part of some indeterminate root nodule. It is defined as a part of an indeterminate root nodule permeated with infection threads full of bacteria, where the plant cells are larger than in the previous zone, and cell division is halted.

The indeterminate root nodule nitrogen fixation zone is a type of indeterminate root nodule, and it is a component that is at least part of some indeterminate root nodule. It is defined as a part of an indeterminate root nodule where each cell contains a large, central vacuole, and the cytoplasm is filled with fully differentiated bacteroids that are actively fixing nitrogen. Typically, these cells are provided with leghemoglobin by the plant, resulting in a distinct pink color.

The indeterminate root nodule senescent zone is both a type of indeterminate root nodule and a part of some indeterminate root nodules. It is defined as the part of an indeterminate root nodule where plant cells and their bacteroid contents are being degraded, with the breakdown of the heme component of leghemoglobin resulting in a visible greening at the base of the nodule.

Anoxic water is a type of liquid water and is defined as water which lacks dissolved oxygen. It is also a type of substance that complements something that, at the very least, includes a part that intersects with something having dioxygen and something that possesses some quality of being dissolved. Furthermore, anoxic water is exactly synonymous with anaerobic water and is relatedly synonymous with reducing water.
The forest biome is a type of forest ecosystem defined as a forest ecosystem in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.

The woodland biome is a type of terrestrial biome and also a type of entity that includes, at minimum, some areas of woodland. It is defined as a terrestrial biome that encompasses, within its entire spatial extent, woody plants spaced sufficiently apart to allow light to penetrate, thereby supporting communities of herbaceous plants or shrubs located closer to the woodland floor.
The shrubland biome is a type of terrestrial biome, defined by dense groups of shrubs across its entire spatial extent.
The grassland biome is a type of grassland ecosystem defined as a grassland ecosystem in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.

The savanna biome is a type of woodland biome, which is defined as a woodland biome with seasonal water availability. It includes trees that are spaced sufficiently far apart to allow an unbroken layer of grass, sedge (Cyperaceae), or rush (Juncaceae) communities to thrive.

A desert biome is the same as something that intersects a desert ecosystem and something that is at least determined by some ecological community. It is a type of desert ecosystem and also a type that at least overlaps some desert area, as well as being a type that is at least determined by some ecological community. Furthermore, a desert biome is defined as a terrestrial biome which loses more liquid water by evapotranspiration than is supplied by precipitation and includes communities adapted to these conditions.

The tundra biome is a type of terrestrial biome and a type of something that at least overlaps some area of tundra. It is defined as a terrestrial biome which comprises a tundra ecosystem that has reached its climax community.

The mangrove biome is identified as a terrestrial biome and is characterized by containing mangrove swamps as a component within its ecosystem. It is defined as a terrestrial biome that encompasses areas populated by mangrove plants, belonging to the Rhizophoraceae family. These plants are uniquely adapted to endure high salinity levels, anoxic conditions, and frequent tidal inundations. Typically, mangrove biomes are found in proximity to tropical and sub-tropical estuaries and depositional marine coastal environments. These environments are marked by the accumulation of fine sediments, often rich in organic content, in locations shielded from strong wave action.

The temperate desert biome is both a type of desert biome and a type of temperate environment. It is defined as a desert biome that features communities adapted to intermediate insolation, low rainfall, and significant temperature variations between winter and summer, with winter temperatures possibly falling below 0 degrees Celsius. In this biome, some precipitation may fall as snow.

The tropical desert biome is a specific kind of desert biome and also falls under the category of tropical environments. It is defined by having communities adapted to temperatures above a monthly average of 18 degrees Celsius, experiencing high daily temperature ranges of approximately 20 degrees Celsius, and receiving very high insolation owing to inhibited cloud formation, along with very low precipitation. Additionally, tropical desert biomes situated near coasts with cold upwellings might exhibit cooler temperatures and reduced insolation due to fog.

The subtropical desert biome is a type of desert biome and also falls under the category of a subtropical environment. It is defined as a desert biome characterized by communities that are adapted to temperatures exceeding a monthly average of 18 degrees Celsius, experiencing high daily temperature ranges of approximately 20 degrees Celsius. This biome is distinguished by high insolation, which is lower than that of a tropical desert biome, inhibited cloud formation, and very low precipitation. When subtropical desert biomes are situated near coasts with cold upwellings, they may exhibit cooler temperatures and reduced insolation due to fog.

The montane desert biome is a type of desert biome and also falls under the category of entities that possess some montane quality. It is defined as a desert biome located in regions elevated above sea level, with its community structure influenced by the environmental conditions dependent on elevation.

The polar desert biome is a type of desert biome as well as a type of polar environment. It is defined as a desert biome that receives low levels of sunlight (insolation), has an annual precipitation of less than 250 millimeters, and experiences a mean temperature of less than 10 degrees Celsius during its warmest month. Additionally, temperature changes in polar deserts frequently cross the freezing point of water.
The subtropical savanna biome is a specific type of both savanna and subtropical biomes. It is defined as a savanna biome that experiences subtropical climate patterns.
The tropical savanna biome is a type of savanna biome as well as a type of tropical biome. It is defined as a savanna biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.

The temperate savanna biome is a specific type of savanna biome, as well as a type of temperate biome. It is defined as a savanna biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with the prairie biome.

The flooded savanna biome is a specific type of savanna biome characterized by its very wet to saturated soil moisture content. It is defined as a savanna biome but with the distinctive feature of having soil that intersects with properties of being wet, meaning it must have at least some parts that are considerably moist. Additionally, the flooded savanna biome is broadly synonymous with a swamp and is also relatedly referred to as a marsh.
The subtropical grassland biome, which is a type of subtropical grassland, is defined as a subtropical grassland where dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.

:tropical_grassland_biome rdfs:subClassOf :tropical_grassland .
text: tropical grassland biome is a type of tropical grassland.
The temperate grassland biome is a type of temperate environment and is also known as a type of temperate grassland. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with the prairie biome.

The Montane Grassland biome is a type of Montane Grassland and a type of entity that possesses some quality of being Montane. It is defined as a grassland biome which occurs in regions elevated above sea level, with its community structure determined by elevation-dependent environmental conditions.

The flooded grassland biome is a type of flooded grassland. This biome is characterized by being an intersection of areas that have soil and areas that possess the quality of being wet, indicating that it consists of regions with soil that are at least partially wet.

The coniferous forest biome, a type of needleleaf forest, is defined as a forest biome containing densely packed populations or communities of coniferous trees. This configuration strongly limits light penetration to the forest floor.
The broadleaf forest biome is a type of broadleaf forest characterized by dominant ecological communities that have reached their climax successional state.
A mixed forest biome is a type of mixed forest characterized by being an ecological community that has reached its climax successional state, where dominant communities are established.
The Mediterranean forest biome, a type of Mediterranean forest, is defined as a forest where dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
The tropical broadleaf forest biome is a type of tropical broadleaf forest characterized by dominant ecological communities that have reached their climax successional state.
The subtropical broadleaf forest biome is a type of subtropical broadleaf forest characterized by dominant ecological communities that have reached their climax successional state.
The temperate broadleaf forest biome, a type of temperate broadleaf forest, is defined as a broadleaf forest subject to temperate climate patterns.
Environmental condition is a type of physical quality and is defined as a range of a determinate quality or combination of qualities that are present in an environmental system.

Tropical refers to a type of environmental condition characterized by high yearly solar irradiance per unit area. Specifically, in tropical conditions, the Sun reaches a subsolar point at least once during the solar year. This phenomenon results in a hot and moist climate year-round at low elevations, where the monthly average temperature remains above 18 degrees Celsius.

Subtropical is classified as a type of environmental condition. It is defined as a subtropical condition when an environmental system experiences greater solar irradiance compared to systems with temperate conditions, yet less than those in tropical conditions. Specifically, at low elevations, this condition is characterized by having eight months of the year with average temperatures of 10 degrees Celsius or higher, and the coldest monthly temperature averages between 2 and 13 degrees Celsius.

Temperate is a type of environmental condition defined as a state in which an environmental system receives less solar irradiance than those with subpolar conditions but greater than those with subtropical conditions. It is exactly synonymous with tepid climate.
The Mediterranean is a type of subtropical climate. A Mediterranean condition, defined as a subtropical condition, is characterized by hot dry summers and winters with moderate to high rainfall.

The Mediterranean woodland biome is a type of subtropical woodland biome as well as a type of Mediterranean biome. It is defined as a subtropical woodland biome that includes communities adapted to hot to warm, dry summers, mild to cold, rainy winters, and the influence of large, usually marine, bodies of water.

The subtropical coniferous forest biome is a type of coniferous forest biome and also a type of subtropical forest. It is defined as a coniferous forest biome which is subject to subtropical climate patterns.
The tropical coniferous forest biome, which is a type of tropical needleleaf forest, is defined as a coniferous forest biome that is subject to tropical climate patterns.

The temperate coniferous forest biome is a type of coniferous forest biome and also a type of temperate forest. It is defined as a coniferous forest biome that is subject to temperate climate patterns.

The temperate mixed forest biome, which is a type of temperate mixed forest, is defined as a temperate mixed forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
The subtropical shrubland biome is a type of shrubland biome and also a type of subtropical biome. It is defined as a shrubland biome subject to subtropical climate patterns.
The tropical shrubland biome is a type of shrubland biome and also a type of tropical biome. It is defined as a shrubland biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.

The temperate shrubland biome is a type of shrubland biome and also a type of temperate biome. It is defined as a shrubland biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with the prairie biome.

The montane shrubland biome is a type of shrubland biome and also a type of montane biome. It is defined as a biome that occurs in regions elevated above sea level, characterized by a community structure determined by elevation-dependent environmental conditions.

The Mediterranean shrubland biome is a type of subtropical shrubland and Mediterranean biome, characterized by communities adapted to hot to warm, dry summers, mild to cold, rainy winters, and the influence of large, usually marine, bodies of water.

:xeric_shrubland_biome rdfs:subClassOf :shrubland_biome .
text: xeric shrubland biome is a type of shrubland biome.

An anthropogenic terrestrial biome, also known exactly as an anthrome or human biome, is a type of terrestrial biome that intersects with terrestrial biomes that have, at the very least, formed as a result of some degree of anthropisation. In essence, an anthropogenic terrestrial biome is defined as a terrestrial biome whose community structures are determined by human activity. This definition encapsulates its connection to both terrestrial biomes in general and those specifically altered or formed through human influence.
The tropical woodland biome is a type of woodland biome and also a type of tropical biome, defined as a woodland biome which is subject to tropical climate patterns.
The temperate woodland biome is a type of woodland biome and also a type of temperate biome. It is defined as a woodland biome which is subject to temperate climate patterns.
The subtropical woodland biome is a type of woodland biome and also a type of subtropical biome, defined as a woodland biome that is subject to subtropical climate patterns.

The Montane Savanna Biome is a specific type of Savanna Biome as well as a subtype of Montane Biome. It is defined as a savanna biome that is situated in regions elevated above sea level, with its community structure influenced by environmental conditions dependent on elevation.

The Mediterranean grassland biome, which is a type of Mediterranean grassland, is defined as a subtropical grassland biome. It encompasses communities adapted to hot to warm, dry summers and mild to cold, rainy winters, under the influence of large, usually marine, bodies of water.

The subtropical dry broadleaf forest biome is a type of subtropical dry broadleaf forest defined as a subtropical dry broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.

The subtropical moist broadleaf forest biome, a type of subtropical moist broadleaf forest, is defined as a subtropical moist broadleaf forest in which dominant ecological communities have reached their climax successional state.
The tropical dry broadleaf forest biome is a type of tropical dry broadleaf forest characterized by its dominant ecological communities having reached their climax successional state.

The tropical moist broadleaf forest biome, also known as the rainforest biome, is a type of tropical moist broadleaf forest. It is defined by the dominant ecological communities within it that have reached their climax successional state.
The Mediterranean savanna biome is a type of subtropical savanna biome and also a type of Mediterranean biome. It is defined as a savanna biome that is subject to Mediterranean climate patterns.
Arid is a type of environmental condition characterized by an annual precipitation that is less than half of the annual potential evapotranspiration.

Lava is a type of environmental material characterized by several distinct features. It is surrounded, at least partially, by a union of water bodies and the atmosphere. Additionally, lava inherently possesses a quality of increased temperature and primarily derives from magma. Composition-wise, lava is an intersection of environmental materials and substances that have the quality of a liquid. The definition of lava encompasses its nature as a mixture of molten or semi-molten rock, volatiles, and solids which have extruded beyond a planetary crust.

Felsic lava is a type of lava that is high in silica (more than 69 percent by weight), aluminium, potassium, sodium, and calcium, resulting in a polymerized liquid that is rich in feldspar and quartz. This type of lava has a higher viscosity compared to other magma types and can erupt at temperatures ranging from 650 to 750 °C. However, unusually hot rhyolite lavas, with temperatures exceeding 950 °C, can flow for many tens of kilometres. Felsic lava is also precisely known as silicic lava.

Intermediate lava, which is also precisely known as andesitic lava, is a type of lava characterized by its specific composition and properties. Compared to felsic lava, intermediate lava contains lower levels of aluminium and silica, with its content ranging between 52 and 63 percent by weight, and it is usually richer in magnesium and iron. This composition results in a temperature range for intermediate lava between 750 and 950 degrees Celsius, which destroys polymerized bonds, leading to more fluid behavior and a greater tendency to form phenocrysts than felsic lavas. The higher content of iron and magnesium in intermediate lava typically results in a darker groundmass and may also lead to the occasional presence of amphibole or pyroxene phenocrysts.

Mafic lava is a type of lava which, relative to other lava types other than ultramafic lava, is characterized by a high ferromagnesian content and low aluminium and silica content, with silica comprising between 45 and 52 percent of its weight. Additionally, mafic lava is also known by its synonym, basaltic lava.
Ultramafic lava is a type of lava defined as having a very high magnesium oxide content and less than 45 percent silica by weight, relative to other lava types.

Basalt is the same as something that is an intersection of an igneous rock and something that at least derives from some mafic lava. Additionally, basalt is a type of igneous rock and also a type of substance that at least derives from some mafic lava. Moreover, basalt is defined as a volcanic rock formed by the rapid cooling of basaltic lava.

Coastal scrubland is defined as a type of scrubland area that intersects with areas that are at least partly part of some sea coast. Additionally, coastal scrubland is considered a type of area that is part of or related to the sea coast. A more specific definition given to coastal scrubland is that it is a scrubland which is part of a coast. Moreover, coastal scrubland is narrowly synonymous with the term coastal chaparral.

Polar is a type of environmental condition, defined as a polar condition being an environmental condition in which an environmental system receives low, yearly solar irradiance per unit area, resulting in colder climatic conditions. Additionally, polar has a related synonym, frigid.
An oak woodland is a type of woodland ecosystem characterized by a tree community primarily composed of oak trees.

A conifer woodland is a type of woodland ecosystem characterized by a tree community primarily composed of coniferous trees from the Division Pinophyta, also known as Coniferophyta or Coniferae. This defines a conifer woodland as a woodland with a specific composition.
Juniper woodland is a type of conifer woodland, defined as a woodland with a tree community primarily composed of trees of the genus Juniperus.

Desert scrubland is defined as a scrubland that is located in a desert and is synonymous with desert scrub. It is characterized as being the same as an intersection of a scrubland area, having at least some arid qualities, and overlapping with a desert area to some extent. Moreover, desert scrubland is categorized as a type of scrubland area, a type of region that has some arid qualities, and a type of area that overlaps with some desert area.
A boulder is a type of piece of rock defined as a piece of rock with a grain size above 300 millimetres in diameter.

Pinyon juniper woodland is a type of conifer woodland which is defined as a conifer woodland with a tree community primarily composed of trees from the subsection Cembroides of the genus Pinus and the genus Juniperus.

A cropland biome is a type of cropland ecosystem and is also categorized as a type of entity that has, at least partially, formed as a result of anthropisation. It is defined as a cropland ecosystem in which dominant ecological communities are maintained in a stable state, mimicking a climax community, through human intervention.
A village biome, which is a type of anthropogenic terrestrial biome, contains settlements such as villages, towns, and/or small cities. It is primarily used for agricultural activity.
The rangeland biome is a type of anthropogenic terrestrial biome, primarily used for the rearing and grazing of livestock.

A dense settlement biome is classified as a type of anthropogenic terrestrial biome, characterized by its primary use for human habitation, recreation, and industry within built structures, with minimal other land use.
An urban biome is a type of dense settlement biome, defined as a dense settlement biome that has been urbanized.

The subpolar coniferous forest biome is a specific type of both the coniferous forest biome and the subpolar environment. It is defined as a coniferous forest biome that includes communities adapted to subpolar conditions. Additionally, this biome is closely synonymous with boreal forest and taiga.

Subpolar is a type of environmental condition defined as a condition in which an environmental system receives low, yearly solar irradiance per unit area and is surrounded by large land masses. This situation leads to very cold winters with temperatures potentially dropping to around -40 degrees Celsius, and summers that last no more than 3 months of the year with a 24-hour average temperature of at least 10 degrees Celsius. Furthermore, subpolar is exactly synonymous with boreal and subarctic.

The freshwater lake biome is a type of freshwater biome and also falls under the category of things that, at the very least, include some part of a freshwater lake. Moreover, it is defined as a biome characterized by the presence of a freshwater lake.

A freshwater river biome is a type of freshwater biome and is also a type of something that at least has part some freshwater river. It is defined as a freshwater biome which is determined by a freshwater river.
An environmental system is a type of system defined as a system with the disposition to environ one or more material entities. It is exactly synonymous with the term "environment."

A mineral deposit is a type of surface landform and it is defined as a physiographic feature which has unusually high concentrations of one or more minerals. It is also exactly synonymous with mineral ore deposit and has a narrow synonym, ore deposit.

Mineral material is defined as an environmental material that is primarily composed of some substance naturally occurring, solid, and stable at room temperature, with a chemical formula, usually abiogenic, and an ordered atomic structure. It is synonymous with substances that are both environmental materials and primarily composed of minerals. Furthermore, mineral material is categorized as a type of solid environmental material and as a type of substance that is primarily composed of minerals.

A white smoker is a type of marine hydrothermal vent characterized by emitting lighter-hued minerals, such as those containing barium, calcium, and silicon. These alkaline hydrothermal vents also continuously generate acetyl thioesters, providing both the starting point for more complex organic molecules and the energy needed to produce them.

A fluid cline is a type of fluid front and is also broadly synonymous with the term "cline." It is characterized by being a part of something that encompasses at least a portion of a union of gaseous environmental material and liquid environmental material. The definition of a fluid cline highlights its nature as a fluid front that is thin in comparison to the fluid mass it is part of. Moreover, across this fluid cline, a property of that fluid mass varies greatly over a short vertical distance, relative to the variation across the entire fluid mass.
Pycnocline is a type of fluid cline and is defined as a cline across which the density of a fluid changes rapidly. Additionally, it is synonymously related to a stable density gradient.

A nutricline within a water body is the same as the intersection of a nutricline and at least part of a water body. This is considered a type of nutricline and also a type of entity that is at least part of some water body. It is defined as a nutricline which is part of a water body and is related to the synonym "nutrient gradient."
Seep is a type of spring and is defined as a spring in which water has filtered through permeable earth to the surface.

A cold seep is a type of seep that is at least adjacent to some ocean or sea floor. It is defined as an area of the ocean floor where hydrogen sulfide, methane, and other hydrocarbon-rich fluids seepage occurs. Cold seeps are distinct from hydrothermal vents in that the emissions from cold seeps are of the same temperature as the surrounding seawater, whereas the emissions from hydrothermal vents are super-heated. Additionally, cold seeps are also known as hydrocarbon seeps or methane seeps.

A hydrothermal seep is a specific type of seep characterized by the diffuse flow of geothermally heated fluids with high concentrations of methane. This particular seep is recognized as an intermediate between cold seeps and hydrothermal vents. It is also referred to by its related synonym, "hot seep."

Water vapour is a type of gaseous environmental material and is also something that is composed primarily of water. It is defined as a vapour which is the gas phase of water. Furthermore, water vapour is exactly synonymous with aqueous vapor, aqueous vapour, and water vapor.

The atmosphere is a type of fluid layer that is at least adjacent to some astronomical body and is composed primarily of materials that are both environmental and have the quality of a gas. Additionally, an atmosphere is defined as a layer of gases surrounding a material body of sufficient mass, which is held in place by the gravity of the body.

Atmospheric water vapour is defined as water vapour that is part of an atmosphere and is the same as something that intersects with both water vapour and something that is at least part of some atmosphere. It is a type of water vapour, and it also qualifies as a type of entity that is at least part of some atmosphere. Additionally, atmospheric water vapour serves a role as a greenhouse gas. Furthermore, "atmospheric water vapor" is an exact synonym for atmospheric water vapour.

Siltstone is a type of clastic sedimentary rock and is considered a type of material that primarily derives from silt. It is defined as a sedimentary rock mainly composed of silt, with a grain size in the silt range. This composition makes it finer than sandstone yet coarser than claystones.

Claystone is a type of clastic sedimentary rock which is primarily composed of clay-sized particles, making it a subset of materials that at least derive from some form of clay. Its definition emphasizes that it is a clastic sedimentary rock with a composition mainly of clay-sized particles.

Clastic sedimentary rock falls under the category of sedimentary rocks. These rocks are defined by their composition, which includes silicate minerals and rock fragments transported by moving fluids. The primary components of clastic rocks are quartz, feldspar, rock (lithic) fragments, clay minerals, and mica, although numerous other accessory minerals may also be present and can be locally important.

Mudstone is a type of clastic sedimentary rock and is also a type of substance that, at a minimum, derives from mud. It is defined as a clastic sedimentary rock that contains a mixture of at least one-third of silt- and one-third of clay-sized particles. However, mudstone is distinctly different from lime mudstone.

Lime mudstone is a type of limestone that is primarily composed of either clay-size or both silt-size and clay-size detrital (transported) carbonate grains. Furthermore, lime mudstone is exactly synonymous with calcilutite and cementstone.
Slate is a type of metamorphic rock that is fine-grained, foliated, homogeneous, and at least derives from some clastic sedimentary rock.
A structural basin is a type of depressed landform, defined as a geological depression formed by tectonic warping of previously flat-lying rock strata.

An ecoregion is a type of ecosystem and also a type of entity that constitutes at least part of an ecozone. It is defined as a large unit of land or water containing a geographically distinct assemblage of species, natural communities, and environmental conditions.

Water ice is the same as something that is the intersection of ice and something that is at least composed primarily of some liquid water. It is a type of solid environmental material, a type of ice, and a type of something that is at least formed as a result of something that is the union of the freezing of water into water ice, compaction process, and the desublimation of water vapor into ice. Moreover, water ice is defined as ice which is formed from water and has a related synonym, ice.
A pingo scar is a type of depressed and surface landform that originates at least partially from a pingo. It is defined as a depression caused by the collapse of a pingo.

An ice lens is a type of land ice mass and is defined as an ice mass which is formed when moisture, diffused within soil or rock, accumulates and freezes in a localized zone, wedging soil or rock apart. It is also exactly synonymous with ice lenses.

An ecozone is a type of ecosystem and also a type of entity that constitutes at least part of a biosphere. It is defined as large areas of a planetary surface within which organisms have been evolving in relative isolation over long periods of time. This isolation is due to geographic features, such as oceans, broad deserts, or high mountain ranges, which act as barriers to migration.

A layer is a type of material entity and also falls under the category of something that possesses at least some laminar quality. It is defined as a quantity of some material which is spatially continuous, maintains comparable thickness, and usually covers some surface.

A sedimentary stratum is a type of solid layer and also a type of entity that is composed primarily of a combination of soil and sedimentary rock. It is defined as a layer which is composed of sedimentary rock or soil, with internally consistent characteristics that distinguish it from other layers. Furthermore, "stratum" is a broad synonym for sedimentary stratum.

The lake layer is the same as something that intersects with both the aquatic layer and something that is at least part of some lake. Additionally, the lake layer is recognized as a type of aquatic layer and also as a type of entity that is at least part of some lake. Furthermore, the lake layer is defined as a layer which is part of a lake.

An amictic lake is a type of lake that is characterized by a surface layer that intersects with water ice, indicating that it has parts that are at least adjacent to some form of water ice. It is defined as a lake which is permanently covered by ice, does not mix, and exhibits inverse cold water stratification, whereby the water temperature increases with depth below the ice surface. Additionally, amictic lakes are distinct and not overlapping with holomictic lakes.

A holomictic lake is a type of lake characterized by its mixing process. Specifically, a holomictic lake is one that mixes at least once per year, a phenomenon caused by a uniform temperature distribution from the upper to lower layers of the lake. Additionally, it is also known by its related synonym, non-meromictic lake.

A dimictic lake is a type of holomictic lake that mixes from top to bottom during two mixing periods each year, typically during the spring and autumn. During these periods, the lake becomes "isothermal", meaning it is at the same temperature from top to bottom, approximately 4°C. This uniform temperature allows the lake to readily mix from top to bottom in the absence of any temperature or density differences. Dimictic lakes are common in regions with temperate climates. Furthermore, dimictic lakes are distinct from polymictic and monomictic lakes, indicating that these types of lakes do not share the same mixing characteristics.

A polymictic lake, defined as a holomictic lake that is too shallow to allow thermal stratification and can mix from top to bottom throughout the ice-free period of the year, is a specific type of holomictic lake. Furthermore, a polymictic lake is distinct and separate from a monomictic lake.
A monomictic lake, which is a type of holomictic lake, is defined as a holomictic lake that mixes from top to bottom during one mixing period each year.

A cold monomictic lake, which is a type of monomictic lake, is defined as a monomictic lake that is covered by ice for much of the year. It only mixes when its surface ice melts, and during this period, the lake lacks thermal stratification.

A warm monomictic lake is a specific type of monomictic lake characterized by not freezing and remaining thermally stratified for most of the year. It only undergoes mixing during winter when the cooler temperatures reduce stratification.
A cold polymictic lake, which is a type of polymictic lake, is defined as a polymictic lake that is covered by ice in winter.
A warm polymictic lake, which is a type of polymictic lake, is defined as a polymictic lake that is not covered by ice at any point during the year.

An ice mass is equivalent to something that is both a mass of solid material and primarily composed of water ice. It is defined as a mass of water ice and can be broadly synonymous with terms such as "accumulation of ice" and "ice accumulation." Furthermore, an ice mass is a specific type of mass of solid material and is recognized as part of the cryosphere to at least some extent. Additionally, it is characterized by its primary composition, which is predominantly water ice.
A crevice is a type of geological fracture that is defined as a deep fissure in rock, and it is also synonymously referred to as crevice.

The marine layer is defined as a layer that is part of a marine water body. It is equivalent to the intersection of an aquatic layer and part of a union of the ocean and sea. This layer is a specific type of aquatic layer and is also characterized as a part of some marine water body. Additionally, the marine layer is identified as part of the union of the ocean and sea, and it is primarily composed of sea water.

A dry lake bed is a type of solid surface layer and also a type of surface of an astronomical body. It is defined as the bed of a dry lake, meaning it is at least part of some dry lake and has qualities associated with being dry. Additionally, a dry lake bed is characterized by being adjacent to something that is a union of the atmosphere and outer space.

A freshwater river is defined as a river where fresh water flows. It is categorized as a type of river and also as a type of entity that has at least some part fresh water. Additionally, a freshwater river is equivalent to an intersection of a river and an entity that has at least some part fresh water.

A continental margin is identified as a type of slope that forms part of the seafloor. It is characterized by descending from the continental crust to the oceanic crust, overlapping both types of crusts. This geographical feature includes the intersection of the continental shelf, continental slope, and continental rise. Thus, it is defined as a slope that is part of the seafloor, descending from the continental crust to the oceanic crust, and comprising the continental shelf, continental slope, and continental rise.

A Taylor column is a type of fluid astronomical body part, which is characterized by having at least some columnar quality and is formed as a result of mass fluid flow. It is defined as a column of deflected fluid flow that forms in a perturbed, rotating fluid. This column is parallel to the axis of rotation and extends above the obstacle perturbing the fluid in a rigid manner.

An atmospheric Taylor column is the same as the intersection of a Taylor column and something that is at least located in some atmosphere. It is a type of Taylor column and also a type of entity that is at least located in some atmosphere. An atmospheric Taylor column is defined as a Taylor column that is formed in the atmosphere, often forming above islands resulting in vortex streets in the atmosphere.
