Estuarine water is defined as brackish water which is part of an estuary. It is recognized as a type of brackish water and similarly, it is considered a type of water that is at least partially part of a brackish estuary. This implies that estuarine water is essentially the same as the intersection of brackish water with water that is part of a brackish estuary.

An outcrop is a type of surface landform and is defined as a portion of environmental material which protrudes through a surface layer. It is also described as something that is composed primarily of environmental material intersecting with a surface and has the quality of protruding out.

An endolithic environment is defined as an environment that exists within solid rock, which is a type of environmental system and is also characterized by being at least surrounded by some rock. This environment is equivalent to the intersection of an environmental system and something that is at least surrounded by some rock.

A high-pressure environment is defined as an environment where all material entities are exposed to a high ratio of force per unit area. It is characterized as a type of environmental system determined by a specific quality and is synonymous with environments that inherently possess a quality of increased pressure. This definition encapsulates both the concept of environments determined by a quality that includes increased pressure and those where increased pressure is a defining characteristic.

A high temperature environment is equivalent to the intersection of an environmental system determined by a quality and something that possesses a quality of increased temperature. It is categorized as a type of an environmental system defined by a specific quality and also as a type that inherently has a quality of some increased temperature. Furthermore, a high temperature environment is defined as an environment where material entities are subjected to elevated levels of heat radiation, or which have molecules or atoms moving randomly with enhanced levels of average kinetic energy.

A freshwater environment is defined as an aquatic environment that is determined by freshwater, meaning it is the intersection of an aquatic environment and an environment at least determined by some fresh water. It is a type of aquatic environment and also a type of environment that is at least determined by some fresh water. Additionally, a freshwater environment is alternatively termed as water (non-saline) and has an exact synonym, which is a fresh water environment.

The saline water environment is the same as an intersection of an aquatic environment and something that is at least determined by some saline water. It is a type of aquatic environment, a type of saline environment, and a type of something that is at least determined by some saline water. Furthermore, the saline water environment is defined as an environmental system which has its properties and dynamics determined by saline water. It is also alternatively termed as Water (saline).
An extraterrestrial environment is a type of environmental system, which is defined as an environmental system located beyond the Earth's exosphere and away from the Earth's core.

A cold environment is defined as an environment that intersects with environmental systems and possesses at least some quality of decreased temperature. This environment is categorized as a type of environmental system and is also classified as a type that has the quality of some decreased temperature. Furthermore, a cold environment is defined as an environment which has a lower temperature than some local or global average.

A haline environment is a type of environment characterized by high osmolarity. It is also defined as an environment primarily composed of materials that intersect with those having increased levels of sodium chloride. Furthermore, a haline environment is described as an environment where entities are exposed to high concentrations of salt, typically above 2 molar.

A cultivated environment is a type of anthropogenic environment, which means it is an environment modified by humans through the preparation of the land, usually for the purposes of growing crops. It is closely associated with terms such as cropland, which is both a narrow synonym and a related synonym. Other related synonyms for a cultivated environment include agricultural region, cultivated area, cultivated cropland, market garden, range, truck farm, and truck garden, indicating its wide-ranging relevance to various aspects of human-modified natural landscapes for agricultural purposes.
A culturing environment, which is a type of anthropogenic environment, is defined as an environment maintained by humans for the purposes of preparing cell, organ, tissue, and plant tissue cultures.

The anthropogenic environment is a type of environmental system defined as the product of human activity. It is characterized by being the intersection of the environmental system and entities that are at least determined by the outputs of anthropisation. Essentially, the anthropogenic environment is synonymous with systems that are significantly shaped or influenced by human actions.

A high osmolarity environment is equivalent to an intersection of an environmental system determined by a quality and something that possesses at least some increased osmolarity. It is a type of environmental system defined by a quality and also falls under the category of entities that have increased osmolarity. Moreover, a high osmolarity environment is defined as an environment where entities are exposed to high concentrations of solutes.

An acidic environment is defined as an environment in which material entities are exposed to a low pH. It is a type of environmental system determined by a quality, specifically, it is determined by being acidic. This encompasses systems that are characterized by the intersection of entities and qualities, where the entities possess an acidic quality. Essentially, an acidic environment is one that is defined by its acidic nature, lying at the intersection of environmental systems and entities that inherently possess acidic qualities.

An alkaline environment is defined as an environment in which entities are exposed to high pH, typically greater than a pH of 9. It is a type of environmental system determined by a quality and also a type of system that at least has some alkaline quality. This concept is synonymous with the intersection of an environmental system determined by a quality and a system that possesses at least some alkaline quality.

The aquatic environment is the same as something that intersects with an environmental system and something that is at least determined by some liquid water. It is a type of environmental system determined by both a quality and a material. Additionally, the aquatic environment is a type of something that is at least determined by some liquid water. Moreover, the aquatic environment is defined as an environment whose dynamics are strongly influenced by water.
An extreme high temperature environment is a type of high temperature environment characterized by the exposure of entities to temperatures above 80 degrees Celsius.

A rocky slope is defined as a slope that has a surface primarily composed of rock. It is identical to an entity that is both a slope and at least partially comprises an entity that is the intersection of a surface layer and primarily composed of rock. Furthermore, a rocky slope is categorized as a type of slope and as a type of entity that, at a minimum, includes a part that is the intersection of a surface layer and is predominantly made up of rock.

The marine environment is defined as an environment that is determined by a marine water body. It is a type of environmental system that intersects with something determined at least in part by marine water bodies. Additionally, the marine environment is characterized as a type of system that is similarly determined by marine water bodies.

The sea water environment is the same as something that is an intersection of a saline water environment and something at least determined by some sea water. It is a type of saline water environment as well as a type of something that is at least determined by some sea water. The sea water environment is defined as an environmental system determined by seawater and has the exact synonym "ocean water environment."

The brackish water environment is defined as an environment determined by the presence of brackish water. It is a type of saline water environment as well as a type that is at least determined by some brackish water. Furthermore, the brackish water environment is the same as the intersection of a saline water environment and something that is at least determined by some brackish water.

The atmospheric boundary layer, also known exactly as the planetary boundary layer, is defined as the lowest layer of an atmosphere. It is strongly influenced by its contact with a planetary surface, characterized by strong vertical mixing, and in which physical quantities such as flow velocity, temperature, and moisture display rapid fluctuations, indicating turbulence. This layer is equivalent to the intersection of the boundary layer and at least a part of an atmosphere that is adjacent to a planetary surface and serves as a bounding layer of an atmosphere. The atmospheric boundary layer is categorized as a type of atmospheric layer, boundary layer, something that at least bounds an atmosphere, and something that is at least adjacent to a planetary surface.

A planetary surface is defined as a surface layer where the solid or liquid material of a planet comes into contact with an atmosphere or outer space. It is the same as an intersection of the surface of an astronomical body and something that is at least part of some planet. Furthermore, a planetary surface is a type of surface of an astronomical body and also a type of something that is at least part of some planet.

The aquatic layer is defined as a layer in a water mass, itself primarily composed of water. It is equivalent to the intersection of a liquid layer and something that is at least primarily composed of liquid water. Furthermore, the aquatic layer is identified as a type of liquid layer and also as a type that is at least primarily composed of liquid water.

The Deep Chlorophyll Maximum Layer (DCM) is a type of aquatic layer that is also referred to by its exact synonym, DCM, and its related synonym, subsurface chlorophyll maximum layer. This layer is characterized by being a subsurface layer in a water body, typically an ocean or lake, where chlorophyll concentrations reach their maximum. Furthermore, this layer is defined by having at least increased levels of some chlorophyll.
A strand swamp is a type of swamp ecosystem, defined as a swamp that forms linear drainage channels on flatlands.

A dome swamp is defined as a swamp ecosystem that happens to be in an area of intersection between a swamp ecosystem and an area that is at least partially surrounded by a depressed landform. It is characterized by its unique location in a depression, where deeper waters in the center allow trees to grow taller compared to those in the shallower regions around it, forming a dome-like shape. Thus, a dome swamp is both a type of swamp ecosystem and a type of area that is at least partially surrounded by a depressed landform.

A cypress dome is a type of dome swamp, and it is defined as a dome swamp that features a plant community dominated by the Cupressaceae family, often including swamp cypresses. These swamp cypresses usually belong to the genus Taxodium or the species Glyptostrobus pensilis and Actinostrobus pyramidalis. Additionally, cypress dome is exactly synonymous with cypress dome swamp.

A cypress strand swamp is a type of strand swamp characterized by having a plant community dominated by Cupressaceae, often swamp cypresses. These swamp cypresses typically belong to the genus Taxodium or the species Glyptostrobus pensilis and Actinostrobus pyramidalis. Additionally, a cypress strand swamp is also exactly synonymous with the term "cypress strand."

A cypress swamp is a type of swamp ecosystem that is defined as a swamp with a plant community dominated by Cupressaceae, often swamp cypresses. These swamp cypresses typically belong to the genus Taxodium or the species Glyptostrobus pensilis and Actinostrobus pyramidalis.

A gravelly slope is defined as a slope that has a surface primarily composed of gravel. It is identified as a type of slope and is characterized as having at least a part that is an intersection of a surface layer and a composition that is primarily made of gravel. Additionally, a gravelly slope is synonymous with an entity that intersects with both a slope and an entity that has at least a part composed primarily of gravel.

Hillside is defined as a slope that is part of a hill. It is the same as an intersection of something that is a slope and something that is at least part of some hill. Moreover, hillside is a type of slope and also a type of something that is at least part of some hill. Additionally, hillside has a related synonym, brae.

A talus slope, which is exactly synonymous with a scree slope, is a type of slope characterized by having a part that intersects with a surface layer primarily composed of scree. Additionally, it is defined as a slope with a surface layer made up of scree.

Understory is a type of vegetation layer and is part of the union of forest ecosystem and woodland ecosystem. It is defined as a layer of plant life which grows below the canopy without penetrating it. Moreover, understory has exact synonyms such as under story, undergrowth, and understorey.

The shrub layer is a type of vegetation layer that forms part of the union between a forest ecosystem and a woodland ecosystem. It is defined as a layer of vegetation in a woodland or forest consisting of low, woody vegetation of frutescent form.

The herb and fern layer represents a type of vegetation layer that is part of the forest and woodland ecosystems. It is specifically characterized by its herbaceous quality. A detailed definition of the herb and fern layer describes it as a layer within a forest or woodland, consisting of all vascular plant life that stands one metre or less in height. This layer is also known by several exact synonyms, including fern layer, herb layer, herb stratum, herbaceous layer, herbaceous stratum, and herbaceous understory. Additionally, it is related to ground cover, ground vegetation, and the regeneration layer through related synonyms.

The litter layer is recognized as a type of Caro 0000000 and also considered a type of vegetation layer. It is identified as part of, or associated with, ecosystems that are a combination of forest and woodland ecosystems. Additionally, the litter layer is primarily composed of plant litter. Furthermore, the litter layer is exactly synonymous with the ground layer.

The polar biome is the same as something that intersects a biome and something that at least possesses some polar quality. It is a type of biome as well as a type of polar environment. Moreover, the polar biome is defined as a biome which is subject to polar climatic conditions.

Alpine is a type of altitudinal condition, defined as an altitudinal condition that exists in a bearer because the bearer has a monthly mean temperature of less than 10 degrees Celsius and is situated at altitudes above the tree line and below the snowline.

Subalpine is a type of altitudinal condition that is defined as an altitudinal condition which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being located at an altitude immediately below the tree line of an elevation.

Montane is a type of altitudinal condition, defined as an altitudinal condition which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer being located at an altitude between mid-altitude forests and the tree line.

Altitudinal condition is a type of environmental condition and it is defined as an environmental condition in which ranges of factors such as temperature, humidity, soil composition, solar irradiation, and tree density vary with ranges in altitude.

Nival is a type of altitudinal condition and it is defined as an altitudinal condition which inheres in a bearer by virtue of the bearer having extremely limited vegetation cover, silica-enriched soils, and ground cover dominated by snow and ice at altitudes above the snowline.
Upper montane is a type of montane, defined as a montane condition in which an altitude range falls immediately below the tree line.
Lower montane is a type of montane and is defined as a montane condition in which an altitude range falls immediately above mid-altitude forests.

Montane conifer woodland is a type of conifer woodland and also falls under something that possesses the quality of being montane. It is defined as a conifer woodland located within an altitude range that lies between mid-altitude forests and the tree line.
A maize field is a type of agricultural field, defined as a field used for the cultivation of corn or related crop plants.
Root matter is a type of organic material and something that comprises at least part of a root. It is defined as an organic material primarily composed of a portion of plant root.
Autoclaved sand is a type of sand that is defined as sand that has been sterilized by exposure to high-pressure saturated steam at at least 121 degrees Celsius.
A field is a type of astronomical body part and is defined as an unbroken expanse, as of ice.

The marine mesoscale eddy field is identified as a specific type of field, which is characterized by several key features. Firstly, it is equivalent to an intersection of a field and an entity that is at least primarily composed of mesoscale marine eddies. Moreover, it is explicitly defined as a type of entity that must have, at a minimum, a part that includes mesoscale marine eddies, and also as a type of entity that is predominantly made up of these mesoscale marine eddies. The definition of the marine mesoscale eddy field clarifies that it is an expanse of marine water containing coherent vortices along with a diverse array of other structures like filaments, squirts, and spirals. It is distinguished by temperature and salinity anomalies accompanied by flow anomalies that nearly achieve geostrophic balance. Despite the surface expression of mesoscale eddies being visible in satellite imagery of sea surface height or temperature, these structures are inherently three-dimensional, extending down into the pycnocline.
An ice cap climatic condition falls under the category of polar types and is defined by a characteristic where the monthly average temperature does not exceed 0 degrees Celsius.

The vegetation layer is synonymous with a layer that represents the intersection of a layer and an entity that is, at least, primarily composed of viridiplantae. It is defined as a layer determined by a form of vegetation, serving as a type of layer in its own right. Furthermore, the vegetation layer is categorized as a part of entities that intersect with both ecosystems and ecological communities, which are, at least, partially composed of viridiplantae. In addition to its primary composition, the vegetation layer is also identified as a type of entity that is primarily made up of viridiplantae. This layer is commonly referred to by several related synonyms, including forest layer, forest stratum, woodland layer, and woodland stratum.
Granite is a type of igneous rock, defined as a portion of igneous rock that is intrusive, felsic, granular, and phaneritic.

Alkaline water is identical to something that is both a form of liquid water and something that possesses at least some alkaline quality. It is a specific type of liquid water as well as a type of substance that has some degree of alkalinity. Moreover, alkaline water is defined as a portion of water with a pH greater than 7.

Acidic water is defined as a portion of water with a pH less than 7, which is also the same as something that is the intersection of liquid water and something that possesses at least some acidic quality. Additionally, acidic water is identified as a type of liquid water and a type of substance that has at least some acidic quality.
A limestone cave is a type of solutional cave and is defined as a cave formed in limestone, usually by dissolution of limestone by acidic groundwater.
A solutional cave is a type of cave characterized by its formation through the dissolution of soluble rock or other solid materials such as limestone, chalk, dolomite, gypsum, salt, or marble.
A primary cave is a type of cave that is defined as a cave formed at the same time as the surrounding rock.

An inflationary cave is a type of volcanic cave characterized by its unique formation process. It is defined as a cave that forms when pressurised lava pushes against the surrounding rock and subsequently drains away.

An erosional cave is a type of cave that is also classified under entities formed as a result of planetary erosion. It is defined as a cave formed by the erosion caused by flowing streams carrying rocks or sediments.

A glacier cave is a type of cave that is specifically found within or under a glacier. This kind of cave is defined as a cave formed within or under a glacier. Additionally, it is a variety of something that must be located in at least some glacier.
An ice cave is a type of cave and is also a type of something that is at least a location of some ice mass. It is defined as a bedrock cave which contains year-round ice formations.
A talus cave is a type of cave characterized by the definition that it is formed by the openings between large boulders which have fallen into a random heap.
An anchialine cave is a type of cave that features at least one anchialine pool as part of its structure. It is defined as a cave which contains an anchialine pool.

An anchialine pool, which is a type of pond, is defined as a landlocked water body with a subterranean connection to the ocean, featuring fresh water towards its surface and saline water in its deeper layers. It is also exactly synonymous with the term anchialine pond.
A vadose cave is a type of cave that not only overlaps some vadose zone but is also defined as a cave which is within a vadose zone.
The tundra climatic condition, a type of environmental condition, is defined as a polar condition in which at least one month's average temperature exceeds 0 degrees Celsius.

Agricultural waste material is a type of waste material defined as waste produced as a result of various agricultural operations. This includes manure and other wastes from farms, poultry houses, and slaughterhouses; harvest waste; fertilizer run-off from fields; pesticides that enter into water, air, or soils; and salt and silt drained from fields. Furthermore, agricultural waste material is broadly synonymous with agricultural waste.

Household waste material is a type of waste material, defined as waste usually generated in the residential environment. Waste with similar characteristics may be generated in other economic activities and can thus be treated and disposed of together with household waste. Additionally, household waste material is broadly synonymous with household waste.

Biological waste material is a type of waste material that is at least composed primarily of organic waste material. It is defined as waste containing mostly natural organic materials, such as remains of plants, animal excrement, biological sludge from wastewater treatment plants, and so forth. Furthermore, biological waste material is broadly synonymous with biological waste.

Dry woodland is a type of woodland ecosystem, and it also falls under the category of a tropical environment. Furthermore, it is characterized by at least having some tropical marine condition. A dry woodland is defined as a woodland that exists in areas of rain shadow within a tropical marine climate, receives very little rainfall, has soils that drain quickly, and is populated by trees adapted to dry climates, featuring thick bark, small leaves, and a tendency to shed their leaves. Additionally, dry woodland is precisely synonymous with a xerophytic ecosystem.
A tropical marine condition, a type of tropical condition, is defined as one in which the ocean strongly influences the climate, characterized by the occurrence of both a wet and dry season.

A tropical marine semi-evergreen forest is a type of tropical forest that encompasses qualities of both tropical marine conditions and semi-deciduous plants. This type of forest, also broadly known as a semi-evergreen forest and exactly termed as a mesophytic ecosystem, is defined by its unique structure and adaptive features due to a long dry season. It has a two-storey layer structure, with a dry canopy and a leaf litter layer that only decays during moist periods. The trees in this forest have very small leaves or shed their leaves to conserve water and flower during the dry season while growing during the wet season.

Humid subtropical is a type of subtropical that is defined as a condition in which an environmental system experiences hot, humid summers, warm to cool dry winters, and average annual precipitation that is either evenly distributed throughout the year or marked by a dry season or drying trend during winter.

Arid subtropical is a type of subtropical condition characterized by an environmental system with an annual average temperature near 18.2 degrees Celsius, where the coldest month averages between 2 and 13 degrees Celsius, coupled with the absence of regular rainfall and high humidity. Furthermore, arid subtropical is exactly synonymous with desert climate and semi-desert climate, while it is relatedly synonymous with semi-arid climate.

Highland subtropical is a type of subtropical that is defined by a condition where increased elevation leads to mild summers, cooler winters, and sometimes snowfall. This occurs when the monthly temperature averages stay below 22 but above -3 degrees Celsius.

Oceanic temperate is a type of temperate that is defined as a condition strongly influenced by oceans and oceanic winds. In these conditions, summers are cool and winters are cool, but not cold, with little frozen precipitation at lower elevations.
Continental temperate is a type of temperate that is defined by a condition influenced by large land masses, characterized by warm to hot summers and often long, cold, and snowy winters.
A cold desert is a type of desert area defined as a desert that experiences hot summers and cold, dry winters, where temperatures fall below 0 degrees Celsius.

A temperate evergreen needleleaf forest is a type of needleleaf forest and also a type of temperate forest. It is considered to be part of the temperate coniferous forest biome to some extent and is characterized by having qualities of evergreen plants. The definition of a temperate evergreen needleleaf forest is an evergreen needleleaf forest that experiences temperate climate patterns. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with a coniferous forest.

The tropical lowland evergreen broadleaf rain forest is identified as a subtype of tropical moist broadleaf forest, which itself is part of the broader tropical moist broadleaf forest biome. It is distinguished by the presence of evergreen plants. This rain forest is defined as a broadleaf forest subjected to tropical climate patterns with high rainfall, situated in lowland areas, and predominated by plants that retain their leaves all year round. Additionally, it is synonymously related to the term "rain forest."

Temperate deciduous broadleaf forest is a type of tropical broadleaf forest and also a type of temperate forest. It is a part of the temperate broadleaf forest biome and includes deciduous plants. Furthermore, it is defined as a deciduous broadleaf forest which is subject to temperate climate patterns.

The temperate deciduous needleleaf forest is a type of needleleaf forest, temperate forest, and it is also a part of the temperate coniferous forest biome to some extent. Furthermore, it aligns with the characteristics of deciduous plants. It is defined as a deciduous needleleaf forest that experiences temperate climate patterns. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with coniferous forest.

Tropical deciduous broadleaf forest is a type of tropical broadleaf forest, and it is also part of the tropical broadleaf forest biome. Additionally, it is characterized by having deciduous plants. This forest is defined as a deciduous broadleaf forest subjected to tropical climate patterns. Furthermore, it is synonymously related to rain forest.

A tropical semi deciduous broadleaf forest is a type of tropical broadleaf forest and is part of the tropical broadleaf forest biome. It is characterized by having some semi deciduous plants. The definition of a tropical semi deciduous broadleaf forest is a semi-deciduous broadleaf forest that is subject to tropical climate patterns. Additionally, it is synonymously related to a rain forest.

A temperate mixed broadleaf forest is a type of temperate mixed forest and can be defined as a temperate mixed forest with communities of trees primarily composed of broad-leaf species. Additionally, it represents an intersection between the temperate broadleaf forest biome and the temperate mixed forest biome.

The temperate mixed needleleaf forest is a type of temperate mixed forest and is part of the temperate mixed forest biome to some extent. It is defined as a temperate mixed forest with communities of trees primarily composed of species with needle-like leaves, such as conifers. Additionally, it is also known by its related synonym, coniferous forest.

The tropical semi-evergreen moist broadleaf forest is a subtype of the tropical moist broadleaf forest biome, and it is characterized by possessing qualities of semi-deciduous plants. Additionally, this forest type is also synonymous with the term "rain forest."

The tropical upper montane forest is a type of montane forest, a type of tropical forest, and a type of entity that possesses the quality of being at least somewhat upper montane. It is defined as a montane forest situated in a region experiencing tropical climate patterns that are moderated by enough elevation to fall within upper montane climate patterns.

Tropical lower montane forest is a type of montane forest, tropical forest, and something that possesses the quality of being at least somewhat lower montane. It is defined as a montane forest located in a region subject to tropical climate patterns, which is modulated by a sufficient elevation to encounter lower montane climatic patterns.
Tropical freshwater swamp forest is a type of swamp forest and also a type of tropical forest. It is defined as a freshwater swamp forest which is subject to tropical climate patterns.

The temperate sclerophyllous dry forest is a type of sclerophyllous forest and also a type of temperate forest. It is characterized by being a type of environment that possesses at least some arid qualities. Additionally, it is defined as a sclerophyllous forest that is subject to temperate climate patterns.

Tropical sclerophyllous dry forest is a type of sclerophyllous forest and also a type of tropical forest. It is a type of something that at least has some arid quality. Additionally, it is defined as a sclerophyllous forest which is subject to tropical climate patterns.

The temperate broadleaf evergreen forest is defined as a broadleaf evergreen forest that experiences temperate climate patterns. It is equivalent to the intersection of a temperate broadleaf forest and entities that have at least some evergreen plants. This forest type is categorized as a subtype of temperate broadleaf forest and also falls under entities that are partly within the temperate broadleaf forest biome and entities that possess qualities of evergreen plants.
Temperate freshwater swamp forest is a type of swamp forest and also a type of temperate forest. It is defined as a freshwater swamp forest which is subject to temperate climate patterns.

A tropical needleleaf forest is a type of needleleaf forest and also a type of tropical forest. It is part of the tropical coniferous forest biome. The definition of a tropical needleleaf forest is a needleleaf forest that is subject to tropical climate patterns. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with a coniferous forest.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:tropical_thorn_forest rdfs:subClassOf :tropical_forest .
text: tropical thorn forest is a type of tropical forest.

Tropical mixed needleleaf forest is a type of tropical mixed forest and it is defined as a mixed needleleaf forest which has communities of trees composed primarily of species with needle-like leaves, such as conifers. Moreover, it is also related to and synonymously known as a coniferous forest.
A tropical mixed broadleaf forest is a type of tropical mixed forest characterized by communities of trees that are primarily composed of species with broad leaves.

Tropical mangrove is a type of tropical forest and also a type of something that at least has part some mangrove swamp. Additionally, tropical mangrove has an exact synonym, which is tropical mangrove forest.

Respirable suspended particulate matter is a type of aerosolised and amorphous solid. It is defined as a portion of particulate matter composed primarily of solid particles, each with a diameter of 10 micrometers or less, and is exactly synonymous with PM10.

Snow is a type of environmental material that is also a type of something which, at the very least, has part some air and is the output of some snowfall. Moreover, snow is primarily composed of water ice and is also a type of something that is an intersection of an object aggregate and something that has at least one member being a snow crystal. Snow is defined as an environmental material which is primarily composed of flakes of crystalline water ice.

The littoral zone refers to a specific type of aquatic environment, identifiable as part of various aquatic environments, including seas, lakes, and rivers, that is situated close to the shore. This zone is also a component of some coasts, highlighting its significance across different bodies of water. Essentially, the littoral zone is defined as an aquatic environment that occupies the area near the shore.

An environmental zone is a type of site and also a type of something that is at least part of some environmental system. It is defined as a site which has its extent determined by the presence or influence of one or more components of an environmental system or the processes occurring therein. Additionally, environmental zone has a related synonym, which is environmental area.

The freshwater littoral zone is a type of littoral zone that is at least adjacent to something that is the union of a freshwater lake and a freshwater river. It is defined as a littoral zone which extends offshore from the shore of a freshwater body of water to the limit of occupancy of rooted plants. Additionally, the freshwater littoral zone is synonymously related to a fringing wetland.

The marine eulittoral zone is recognized as a specific type of marine environmental zone, which is part of, or at least adjacent to, the marine littoral zone. It uniquely positions itself at the intersection of the marine supra littoral zone and the marine sub littoral zone. The eulittoral zone is defined by its geographical extent from the spring high tide line, which is rarely inundated, to the spring low tide line, which is frequently inundated. This area is significantly influenced by the wave action and turbulence associated with recurring tides, which continually shape and reform cliffs, gaps, and caves, thereby creating a diverse range of habitats for sedentary organisms. Additionally, the marine eulittoral zone is known by several synonyms, including the foreshore, intertidal zone, mediolittoral zone, and midlittoral zone, highlighting its importance and relevance in marine biology and environmental studies.

The infralittoral zone is a type of marine environmental zone, which is part of the sublittoral zone and is characterized by being dominated by algae. This specific zone typically extends up to five metres below the low water mark. Additionally, the infralittoral zone constitutes at least part of some marine sublittoral zones.

The circalittoral zone is a type of marine environmental zone, which is also a part of some marine sublittoral zones. It is defined as a zone that is part of the sublittoral zone and is dominated by sessile animals such as oysters. This zone typically begins at a depth greater than the infralittoral zone.

An old plant is equivalent to something that is both a whole plant and has the quality of being somewhat old. It is categorized as a type of whole plant and also falls under the category of entities that possess some degree of oldness. Furthermore, an old plant is defined as a whole plant that is relatively old.

A young plant is defined as a whole plant that is relatively young. It is identified as the same as something that intersects with a whole plant and something that at least has the quality of being somewhat young. Furthermore, a young plant falls under the category of a whole plant and is also considered a type of entity that possesses the quality of being young to some extent.

Fine respirable suspended particulate matter is a type of respirable suspended particulate matter and has a definition as a portion of fine respirable suspended particulate matter, which is a form of particulate matter composed primarily of solid particles each with a diameter of 2.5 micrometers or less. Furthermore, fine respirable suspended particulate matter has an exact synonym, PM2.5.

Ultrafine respirable suspended particulate matter is a type of fine respirable suspended particulate matter, defined as a portion of fine respirable suspended particulate matter. This form of particulate matter is composed primarily of solid particles, each with a diameter of 100 nanometers or less.
A house is a type of building and it is defined as a building that provides a dwelling-place for a living entity.
A human house is both a type of house and a type of domestic building.
A domestic garden is a type of garden that has the definition of being a garden associated with a human house, generally through spatial proximity or parthood.
A building part is defined as a construction which is part of a building. It is recognized as a type of human construction and also as something that constitutes at least a part of some building.

An indoor kitchen is a type of building part. It is defined as a room or part of a room primarily used for cooking or food preparation but may also serve other functions such as dining, food storage, dishwashing, or laundry.

A bathroom is a type of room that has the definition: A bathroom is a room which contains a washbasin or other fixture, such as a shower or bath, used for bathing by humans. It has an exact synonym, which is "bathing room." Additionally, it has related synonyms including "toilet" and "washroom."

The living room is a type of room with the definition: "A living room is a room in a human house which is used for social and domestic leisure activities." Additionally, the living room has an exact synonym: "living-room."

A patio is a type of human construction and is defined as a paved outdoor area, adjacent to a house, and used for dining or recreation. It is also noted that a patio is a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some human house.

An indoor toilet is a type of room and also a type of something that has at least a part which is some toilet fixture. It is defined as a room containing a sanitation fixture used primarily for the disposal of human urine and feces. The indoor toilet is broadly synonymous with restroom and toilet, and exactly synonymous with indoor lavatory, lavatory, and toilet room. Additionally, it has synonyms related to it, such as bathroom and restroom.

A room is a type of building part, defined as a building part which is separated from other building parts by one or more interior walls and, optionally, from outdoor areas by one or more exterior walls.

Carbon nanotube enriched soil is a type of enriched soil and something that, at the very least, has increased levels of carbon nanotubes. It is defined as a portion of soil with elevated levels of carbon nanotubes.

The area of rocky shore is a type of intertidal zone and is defined as an intertidal area of a seacoast where solid rock predominates as the substrate. Additionally, it is synonymously related to the term "rocky intertidal shore."
A burrow is a type of tunnel that is defined as a hole or tunnel excavated into the ground by an animal to create a space suitable for habitation, temporary refuge, or as a byproduct of locomotion.

Broadleaf forest is a type of forest ecosystem defined as a forest biome which contains densely packed populations or communities of broadleaf trees, strongly limiting light penetration to the forest floor.

A mixed forest is a type of forest ecosystem defined as a forest ecosystem containing densely packed populations or communities of broadleaf and coniferous trees, which strongly limit light penetration to the forest floor.
Swamp forest is a type of forest ecosystem that at least overlaps some aspects of a swamp ecosystem.
Needleleaf forest is a type of forest ecosystem and has the exact synonym "coniferous forest."

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:sclerophyllous_forest rdfs:subClassOf :forest_ecosystem .
text: sclerophyllous forest is a type of forest ecosystem.

Montane forest is a type of forest ecosystem that is characterized by the intersection of qualities found in both alpine and montane regions. In other words, a montane forest shares the same characteristics as those found in areas that are both part of the forest ecosystem and have qualities associated with either alpine or montane regions or both.

Waterborne particulate matter is defined as particulate environmental material in which small portions of solid material are surrounded by water. It is a type of particulate environmental material that is at least surrounded by some liquid water and composed primarily of solid environmental material.

A lava field is a type of field and also a type of entity that includes at least a part of some lava flow. It is defined as an expanse of flat-lying lava flows, which are generally composed of highly fluid basalt lava and can extend for tens or even hundreds of miles across the underlying terrain. Furthermore, a lava field is exactly synonymous with terms such as lava area, lava bed, and lava plain.

Lava flow is a type of body of liquid and is primarily composed of lava. It forms as a result of an effusive eruption. A lava flow is defined as a moving outpouring of lava, created during a non-explosive effusive eruption.

An andesitic volcano is a type of volcano that is characterized by having at least part of its composition made up of andesite. Furthermore, it is formed as a result of volcanic eruptions that involve the intersection of processes that produce intermediate lava as an output. The definition of an andesitic volcano is a volcano that has been formed due to the eruption of andesitic lava.

A dacitic volcano is a type of volcano that is characterized by at least having a part of dacite. It is also defined as a type of structure that is formed as a result of volcanic eruptions that produce dacitic lava. Specifically, a dacitic volcano is defined as a volcano that has been formed due to the eruption of dacitic lava.

Andesite is a type of igneous rock, which is also a type of something that at least derives from some intermediate lava. It is defined as an extrusive igneous, volcanic rock, of intermediate composition, with aphanitic to porphyritic texture.

Dacite is a type of igneous rock and also a type of substance that at least derives from dacitic lava. The definition of dacite is as follows: Dacite is an igneous, volcanic rock characterized by an aphanitic to porphyritic texture, and it occupies an intermediate composition between andesite and rhyolite. The composition of dacite predominantly includes plagioclase feldspar along with biotite, hornblende, and pyroxene (specifically augite and/or enstatite). It features quartz either as rounded, corroded phenocrysts, or as part of the ground-mass. The plagioclase in dacite ranges from oligoclase to andesine and labradorite. Additionally, sanidine may be present in dacite, albeit in small amounts; however, when it is abundant, it leads to the formation of rocks that transition into rhyolites.

A salt mass is defined as an accumulation of a salt, typically sodium chloride. It is the same as something that intersects the characteristics of being a solid astronomical body part and being at least composed primarily of some salt material. Furthermore, a salt mass is a type of solid astronomical body part and also a type of entity that is at least composed primarily of some salt material.
Dacitic lava is a type of lava defined as lava which is high in silica and low in alkali metal oxides.

A disturbed ecosystem is a type of ecosystem defined as an ecosystem that has been subject to a perturbation, meaning the ecosystem has undergone a pronounced change in response to a change in environmental conditions or other perturbation.
A ravine, which is a type of valley, is defined as a small, narrow, steep-sided valley that is larger than a gully and smaller than a canyon, usually worn by running water.

Roadside is a type of environmental zone, which is also considered to be part of some landmass and is adjacent to a road. Moreover, it is defined as an environmental zone of varying area which is adjacent to a road.
Mixed grassland is a type of grassland ecosystem defined as a grassland which contains a mixture of tall and short grasses. It also has "mixed grassland" as a broad synonym.
The wet meadow ecosystem, which is a specific kind of meadow ecosystem, is defined as a type of wetland characterized by soils that are saturated with water for part or all of the growing season.

A salt glacier is a type of salt mass and a type of surface landform. It is defined as a mass of salt which has erupted onto a planetary surface, usually through sedimentary rock. Additionally, a salt glacier has exact synonyms: namakier and salt fountain.

Atmospheric carbon dioxide is a type of gaseous environmental material and is something that intersects with at least part of some atmosphere and is composed primarily of carbon dioxide. It is defined as an environmental material composed of carbon dioxide in its gaseous form present in an atmosphere.
Environmental disposition is a type of disposition that is defined as a disposition which is realized by an environmental system or system parts thereof.
Carbon pooling disposition, a type of material pooling disposition, is defined as the disposition of an environmental system to sequester and store carbon.

Carbon dioxide pooling disposition, which is a type of carbon pooling disposition, is defined as the disposition of an environment to sequester carbon dioxide, subsequently storing the carbon component thereof.
Material pooling disposition is a type of environmental disposition, which is defined as the disposition of an environmental system to sequester and store some material entity.
A concrete masonry unit is a type of masonry unit that is primarily composed of concrete. It is defined as a large, rectangular masonry unit.

A masonry unit is a type of manufactured product defined as a solid piece of material, usually with a regular shape, used as a component in the construction of buildings. These units are usually composed of materials such as brick, stone, marble, granite, travertine, limestone, cast stone, concrete block, glass block, stucco, tile, or cob.

Concrete is classified as an anthropogenic environmental material and is a type of material that includes masonry cement as part of its composition. It is defined as a composite material composed of an aggregate bonded together with a fluid cement, which hardens over time.

Asphalt concrete is a type of concrete that specifically utilizes refined asphalt as an integral component. This particular composition of concrete, which is also precisely known as asphaltic concrete or road pavement, is defined as a concrete that employs refined asphalt as cement. Essentially, asphalt concrete is a material that incorporates at least a portion of refined asphalt in its composition.

Asphalt, also known as bitumen, is a type of petroleum described as a sticky, black, and highly viscous liquid or semi-solid form. It is exactly synonymous with asphaltum, bitumen, and crude bitumen. Additionally, asphalt is relatedly synonymous with pitch and tar.

Refined asphalt is a manufactured product, an anthropogenic environmental material, and a liquid environmental material that at least derives from some petroleum. It is defined as a sticky, black, and highly viscous liquid or semi-solid with a boiling point above 500 degrees Celsius, obtained from the fractional distillation of crude oil. Additionally, refined asphalt has an exact synonym: refined bitumen.

Masonry cement is identified as an anthropogenic environmental material and serves as a substance used in construction characterized by its ability to set, harden, and thus bind materials together. Additionally, masonry cement is broadly synonymous with cement.

Hydraulic cement, which is a type of masonry cement, is defined as a masonry cement containing activated aluminium silicates or pozzolans, such as fly ash, enabling it to set in wet conditions or underwater.

Non-hydraulic cement is a type of masonry cement characterized by its unique setting process. It sets by reacting with carbon dioxide in the air and cannot set in wet conditions or underwater. Additionally, after setting, it is susceptible to attack by aggressive chemicals.

A building wall is a type of building part, characterized by its role in supporting roofs, floors, and ceilings; enclosing a space as part of the building envelope; giving buildings form; and providing shelter and security.

A boundary wall is a type of constructed barrier, which is usually opaque, constructed from masonry, and of greater structural strength than a fence. Moreover, a boundary wall has a narrow synonym: defensive wall.

A constructed barrier, which is a type of human construction, is a freestanding wall, berm, or fence built to limit the movement of entities across a boundary. This is broadly synonymous with the term "barrier."
A fence is a type of constructed barrier, defined as a constructed barrier that is generally of lighter construction than a wall and used to provide visual sectioning of spaces.
An exterior wall is a type of building wall which separates the interior of a building from the building's surrounding environment, serving as a definition of what an exterior wall entails.

A building envelope is a type of building part that is essentially composed of building parts which physically separate the interior of a building from its surrounding environment, including at least some exterior wall and some building roof. It is defined as a part that provides resistance to air, water, heat, light, and noise transfer, featuring three basic elements: a weather barrier, air barrier, and thermal barrier. Additionally, building envelope is also related to and synonymously known as a building enclosure.

Ceiling is identified as a type of building part and is also recognized as an element that constitutes at least a portion of some room. Additionally, a related synonym for ceiling is described as "an overhead interior surface that covers the upper limit of a room." It is highlighted that a ceiling is not typically regarded as a structural element but rather as a finished surface that hides the underside of the floor or roof structure positioned above.

A building roof is both a type of building part and a type of entity that constitutes at least part of some building envelope. It is defined as the covering on the uppermost part of a building, providing protection from animals and weather, including rain, heat, wind, and sunlight; it is also the framing or structure that supports this covering. Furthermore, the term "roof" is a broad synonym for a building roof.
Thatch is a type of agricultural environmental material defined as material composed of dry vegetation such as straw, water reed, sedge (Cladium mariscus), rushes, or heather.

Brick material is classified as a type of manufactured product, anthropogenic environmental material, and solid environmental material. It is defined as a portion of material derived from a brick, which consists of kneaded clay-bearing soil, expanded clay aggregate, sand, and lime, or concrete that has been either fire-hardened or air-dried.

A brick, which is a type of masonry unit, is defined as a masonry unit that is composed of kneaded clay-bearing soil, expanded clay aggregate, sand and lime, or concrete material, and is either fire-hardened or air-dried.

Plaster is recognized as an anthropogenic environmental material and is defined as a building material that possesses the characteristic of hardening upon reaction with water, a process that liberates heat via crystallization. This substance is produced as a dry powder and transforms into a paste when mixed with water for application. Additionally, plaster is precisely synonymous with both "render" and "stucco."

Gypsum plaster is a type of plaster defined as plaster formed by partially dehydrating gypsum by heating it to approximately 150 degrees Celsius and grinding the product into a powder. Additionally, gypsum anhydride, formed by heating gypsum above 200 degrees Celsius, may also be used as plaster. Gypsum plaster has the exact synonym plaster of Paris.
Cement plaster, also known exactly as cement render and cement stucco, is a type of plaster.

Lime plaster is a type of plaster primarily composed of calcium hydroxide and an inert filler, such as sand. The conversion of the calcium hydroxide to calcium carbonate through a reaction with carbon dioxide in the air causes the plaster to set. Lime plaster is also known by its exact synonyms: lime render, lime stucco, and slaked lime plaster.
Glass is a type of solid environmental material and is defined as an amorphous (non-crystalline) solid, which is often transparent.

Silica-based glass is a type of glass, which is also broadly synonymous with glass itself. It is defined as a glass composed primarily of silicon dioxide, the primary constituent of sand. Additionally, silica-based glass is a type of material that is at least primarily composed of silicon dioxide.

Soda lime glass, which is a type of silica-based glass, is defined as a silica-based glass composed of approximately 75% silicon dioxide, with sodium oxide and calcium oxide constituting most of its remaining composition. It is broadly synonymous with glass and is exactly synonymous with soda-lime-silica glass.

Flat glass, a type of soda lime glass, is defined as being composed of approximately 73% silicon dioxide (silica), 14% sodium oxide, 9% calcium oxide, 4% magnesium oxide, 0.15% aluminium oxide, 0.03% potassium oxide, 0.02% titanium dioxide, and 0.01% iron III oxide. Furthermore, flat glass is precisely synonymous with both plate glass and sheet glass.

Container glass is a type of soda lime glass, defined as a soda-lime glass composed of approximately 74% silicon dioxide (silica), 13% sodium oxide, 10.5% calcium oxide, 1.3% aluminium oxide, 0.3% potassium oxide, 0.2% sulphur trioxide, 0.2% magnesium oxide, 0.04% iron III oxide, and 0.01% titanium dioxide.
Quartz glass is a type of silica-based glass, which is composed of silica in an amorphous (non-crystalline) form. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with both fused quartz and fused silica.

A building floor is a type of solid surface layer and also a type of surface of an astronomical body. It is characterized as something that is at least part of some building. Moreover, a building floor is defined as a surface layer which is part of a building and used for walking.

A brick building floor is a type of building floor and also a type of entity that is, at the very least, primarily composed of brick material. It is defined as a building floor that is composed primarily of brick material or is built from bricks. Additionally, "brick floor" is a broad synonym for brick building floor.

A wooden building floor is a type of building floor, an impermeable surface layer, and something that is at least composed primarily of some wood. It is defined as a building floor that is composed primarily of wood. Additionally, "wooden floor" is considered a broad synonym for wooden building floor, whereas "wooden parquet floor" is identified as a narrow synonym.

A concrete building floor is a type of building floor, an impermeable surface layer, and something that is at least composed primarily of concrete. It is defined as a building floor primarily composed of concrete. Furthermore, it has a broad synonym "concrete floor" and related synonyms including "cement building floor" and "cement floor."

A sandy building floor is a type of building floor and is also a type of something that is at least composed primarily of some sand. It is defined as a building floor that is composed primarily of sand. Additionally, "sandy building floor" has broad synonyms including "sand floor" and "sandy floor."

A glass building floor is a type of building floor and also a type of impermeable surface layer. Additionally, it is characterized as something that is at least composed primarily of some glass. The definition of a glass building floor is that it is a building floor which is composed primarily of glass. Furthermore, "glass floor" is considered a broad synonym for glass building floor.

A dung building floor is a type of building floor that is primarily composed of a material that intersects fecal material and has the quality of being dry. It is defined as a building floor which is primarily made of dried animal feces. Additionally, "dung floor" is a broad synonym for dung building floor.

A stone building floor is a type of building floor, impermeable surface layer, and something that is at least composed primarily of some rock. It is defined as a building floor that is composed primarily of rock. Additionally, stone building floor has broad synonyms including rock floor and stone floor.

A thatched exterior wall is a type of exterior wall that is at least composed primarily of thatch. It is defined as an exterior wall primarily made of thatch. This concept is broadly synonymous with "thatch wall" and "thatched wall," and has an exact synonym, which is "thatch exterior wall."

A stone exterior wall is a type of exterior wall that is primarily composed of rock, which is also a type of something that must be at least composed primarily of some rock. It is defined as an exterior wall that is composed primarily of rock. Additionally, "stone wall" is a broad synonym for stone exterior wall.

A straw exterior wall is a type of exterior wall composed primarily of straw. It is defined as an exterior wall that is primarily made up of straw. Additionally, a straw exterior wall is broadly synonymous with "straw wall."

A mud exterior wall is a type of exterior wall that is at least composed primarily of mud. It is defined as an exterior wall that is primarily made of mud. Additionally, "mud wall" is considered a broad synonym for mud exterior wall.

A pole is identified as a type of object that inherently possesses at least some columnar qualities. It is defined as a solid, cylindrical object or column, characterized by its length being greater than its diameter.

A pole-reinforced mud exterior wall is a type of mud exterior wall that includes at least some parts made of poles. Specifically, a pole-reinforced mud exterior wall is defined as a mud exterior wall supported and reinforced by poles. Additionally, "mud and poles wall" is considered a broad synonym, whereas "mud and poles exterior wall" is an exact synonym for a pole-reinforced mud exterior wall.

A brick exterior wall is a type of exterior wall that is characterized by having at least a part made of brick and is primarily composed of brick material. It is defined as an exterior wall that is built from bricks. Furthermore, "brick wall" is considered a broad synonym for brick exterior wall.
Burnt brick, which is a type of brick, is defined as a brick that has been dried at an elevated temperature in a kiln, furnace, or using similar technology.
Unburnt brick is a type of brick that is defined as a brick which has been air-dried rather than dried at an elevated temperature in a kiln, furnace, or with similar technology.

A burnt brick exterior wall, which is also known as a burnt-brick wall or by its exact synonym, burnt brick exterior wall, is a type of brick exterior wall. This wall is specifically part of a category that includes anything with at least some burnt brick in its composition. Furthermore, a burnt brick exterior wall is defined as an exterior wall that is constructed from burnt bricks.

An unburnt brick exterior wall is a type of brick exterior wall and also falls under the category of entities that include, at least in part, some unburnt brick. By definition, an unburnt brick exterior wall is an exterior wall constructed from unburnt bricks. Additionally, "brick wall" is considered a broad synonym for an unburnt brick exterior wall, while it is exactly synonymous with itself as an unburnt brick exterior wall.

A salt dome is a type of elevated landform, surface landform, salt mass, and something that at least has some domed quality. It is defined as a dome-shaped mass of salt formed when a thick bed of evaporite minerals (mainly salt, or halite) found at depth intrudes vertically into surrounding rock strata, forming a diapir.

A concrete exterior wall is a type of exterior wall that is characterized by being composed primarily of concrete. This type of wall belongs to a category of structures that, at the very least, have a part made up of some concrete masonry unit. Additionally, it is defined as an exterior wall that is primarily made of concrete. Furthermore, "concrete wall" is widely recognized as a broad synonym for a concrete exterior wall.

An iron sheet is a type of manufactured product and a type of something that is composed primarily of iron atoms. It is defined as a mass of iron that has been forged into a roughly planar form with a thickness of less than 6 millimeters.
Salt material is a type of mineral material that is at least composed primarily of some salt.

A sheet iron exterior wall is a type of exterior wall that is built from sheets of iron, which means it is an exterior wall that at least partially comprises iron sheets. It is defined specifically as an exterior wall constructed from iron sheets. This type of wall is also broadly synonymous with "sheet iron wall" and "sheet-iron wall," and it has an exact synonym, "iron sheet wall."

A sheet iron building roof is a type of building roof that is constructed from sheets of iron, essentially being part of something that includes at least some iron sheet. It is defined as a building roof built from sheets of iron. Additionally, "sheet iron roof" and "sheet-iron roof" are considered broad synonyms for sheet iron building roof, while "iron sheet building roof" is an exact synonym.

A thatched building roof is a type of building roof and also a type of structure that is at least primarily composed of thatch. It is defined as a building roof that is built by thatching or out of thatch. Moreover, "thatch roof" and "thatched roof" are broad synonyms for a thatched building roof.

A wooden building roof is a type of building roof that is classified as being primarily composed of wood. This implies that a wooden building roof, in essence, is part of a structure that includes wood as a significant material in its composition. It is defined as a building roof built from wood. Additionally, "wooden building roof" is broadly synonymous with both "wood roof" and "wooden roof."

An asbestos building roof is a type of building roof that is built from asbestos, which is also broadly synonymous with the term asbestos roof. This definition explains that an asbestos building roof specifically refers to a building roof constructed from asbestos.

Tile is a type of manufactured product and is defined as a manufactured piece of hard-wearing material such as ceramic, stone, metal, or even glass. These are generally used for covering roofs, floors, walls, showers, or other objects such as tabletops. Alternatively, tile can sometimes refer to similar units made from lightweight materials such as perlite, wood, and mineral wool, which are typically used for wall and ceiling applications.

A tiled building roof, which is also broadly synonymous with tile roof and tiled roof, and exactly synonymous with tile building roof, is a type of building roof. It is characterized by being a part of something that includes tiles. The definition of a tiled building roof is that it is a building roof constructed using tiles.
A toilet fixture is a type of plumbing fixture that is primarily used for the collection and, in some cases, disposal of human urine and feces. It is broadly synonymous with the term "toilet."

A pit latrine, which is also exactly known as a pit toilet, is a type of latrine that is constructed by digging a hole in the ground. It is essentially a latrine that includes at least a part of a latrine pit.

A diapir is a type of rock intrusion. It is defined as a type of geologic intrusion in which a more mobile and ductilely deformable material is forced into brittle overlying rocks due to its higher buoyancy.
A latrine is a type of toilet fixture with a definition stating that it is a toilet of simple construction relative to a flush or chemical toilet, typically intended for communal use.

A latrine slab is a type of manufactured product and also falls under the category of items that possess at least some fenestrated quality. It is defined as a broad, flat, thick piece of solid material, typically made from stone or concrete, which serves as the floor of a latrine. This slab includes a hole through which excreta are deposited into a latrine pit.

A batholith is a type of igneous intrusion, which is essentially a result of the intersection between the igneous intrusion process and planetary erosion. It is defined as an area of mostly continuous plutonic (igneous intrusive) rock, covering an area larger than 100 square kilometers. Formed in the planetary crust and exposed by erosion, batholiths on Earth are almost always composed mostly of felsic or intermediate rock-types, such as granite, quartz monzonite, or diorite.
A latrine pit is a type of human construction and a type of pit. It is defined as an artificial hole or cavity in the ground used to collect human excreta.

A pit latrine with slab floor is a type of pit latrine and also a type of something that at least has part some latrine slab. It is defined as a pit latrine which has a latrine slab as a floor. Furthermore, it has a broad synonym: pit toilet.

An outhouse is a type of building defined as a small structure, separate from a main building, which covers a pit latrine or a dry toilet. It has exact synonyms such as earth closet, latrine covering, and latrine shelter. Additionally, outhouse is relatedly synonymous with terms like dunny and privy.

Rock intrusion is a type of intrusion that is at least formed as a result of some rock precursor intrusion process and is also composed primarily of some rock. Furthermore, it is defined as an intrusion which is primarily composed of rock that has been formed within a pre-existing fracture in a larger mass of rock.

Sedimentary intrusion is defined as a rock intrusion that is composed primarily of sedimentary rock. This means it is the same as the intersection of rock intrusions and entities that are at least composed primarily of sedimentary rock. Additionally, sedimentary intrusion is categorized as a type of rock intrusion and also as a type of entity that is at least composed primarily of sedimentary rock.

A flush toilet fixture is a type of toilet fixture defined as a toilet fixture which uses water to flush liquid and solid excreta into a sewage containment or processing facility through a drainpipe. It is broadly synonymous with both 'flush toilet' and 'toilet.' Additionally, it is relatedly synonymous with several terms including bog, comfort room, dunny, head, john, lavatory, loo, pot, the heads, and water closet.

A dry toilet fixture is a type of toilet fixture characterized by its method of excreta disposal, which involves using little to no water. The excreta is either removed manually or composted in situ. This type of toilet fixture is also broadly known as a dry toilet.

A chemical toilet fixture is a type of toilet fixture that uses chemicals to deodorize and treat excreta, which is stored in the fixture. This fixture is broadly synonymous with the term "chemical toilet."

A ventilated improved pit latrine is a type of pit latrine defined as a pit latrine that includes a vent pipe fitted to the pit with a flyscreen covering the pipe's outlet. Air currents moving across the outlet of the vent pipe create a vacuum which draws odors out of the latrine's superstructure. It is broadly synonymous with ventilated pit latrine and exactly synonymous with VIP latrine.

A covered latrine is categorized as a building and is defined as a type of entity that intersects with something that must have at least a part that is a latrine and something that must have at least a part that is an outhouse. The definition of a covered latrine is a building that comprises a latrine sheltered by an outhouse.

A covered pit latrine is a type of covered latrine and also a type of structure that includes at least a part of some pit latrine. Moreover, a covered pit latrine is defined as a building which comprises a pit latrine sheltered by an outhouse.

A covered pit latrine with slab floor is a type of covered pit latrine and also a type of structure that includes at least a portion of a latrine slab. It is defined as a building that encompasses a pit latrine with a slab floor, which is protected by an outhouse.

A pour flush toilet fixture is a type of flush toilet fixture defined as a flush toilet fixture into which water is manually poured to dispose of excreta. It has broad synonyms including flush toilet and toilet, and an exact synonym which is pour flush toilet fixture itself. Additionally, it has related synonyms such as bog, comfort room, dunny, head, john, lavatory, loo, pot, the heads, and water closet.

A pour flush pit latrine is a type of pit latrine defined as a pit latrine that includes a water seal (U-trap or siphon) used over one or two offset pits instead of a plain hole or seat, where water is manually poured through the trap to flush excreta into the latrine pit. It is broadly synonymous with the term "toilet" and is relatedly referred to as a "bog," "dunny," and "head."

A factory is a type of industrial building and is also considered a type of entity that includes at least a part of some industrial building. It is defined as an industrial site, usually consisting of buildings and machinery, or more commonly a complex having several buildings, where workers manufacture goods or operate machines processing one product into another. Furthermore, factory has exact synonyms, including "manufactory" and "manufacturing plant."

Atmospheric ozone is defined as an environmental material that is primarily composed of ozone in its gaseous form and is present in at least part of an atmosphere. Additionally, atmospheric ozone is synonymous with itself.

The stratosphere is a type of atmospheric layer that intersects with layers which are at least adjacent to both the mesosphere and the troposphere, and is also a part of the atmosphere. It is defined as the layer of the atmosphere sandwiched between the troposphere and mesosphere. Of the energy that reaches the Earth from the sun, only 3% is absorbed in the stratosphere, but this includes the vitally important process of absorption of ultraviolet radiation by the stratospheric ozone layer. The stratosphere is unique in that it is cloudless and dust-free, and almost unaffected by the turbulent conditions of the underlying level of the atmosphere. (Source: WRIGHT).

The mesosphere is defined as part of the Earth's atmosphere which is situated between the stratosphere and the thermosphere, where the temperature decreases with altitude to the atmosphere's absolute minimum. It is a type of atmospheric layer that intersects with areas at least adjacent to both the stratosphere and the thermosphere and is a part of the atmosphere.

The troposphere is an atmospheric layer that intersects with both the planetary surface and the stratosphere, being at least adjacent to each and forming part of the atmosphere. It is defined as the lowest among the concentric layers of the atmosphere, situated between the Earth's surface and the tropopause. This layer is characterized by its significant atmospheric turbulence and as the primary generator of the Earth's weather. It encompasses almost all water vapor and aerosols, along with three-quarters of the atmosphere's total gaseous mass. Within the troposphere, the temperature decreases with an increase in height at an average rate of 6.5°C per kilometer, and it is topped by either a temperature inversion or an isothermal layer at the tropopause, according to WHIT.

The thermosphere is a type of atmospheric layer that intersects with a part of the atmosphere and is adjacent to the mesosphere. It is defined as a part of the earth's atmosphere that begins at about 50 miles (80 kilometers) above the earth's surface, extends to outer space, and is characterized by steadily increasing temperature with height.

The ozone layer is a type of atmospheric layer that forms part of the stratosphere and is characterized by increased levels of ozone. It is defined as a layer of gases in the stratosphere which contains high concentrations of ozone gas relative to other parts of the atmosphere. Additionally, the ozone layer is also referred to as the ozone shield, and it has a related synonym which is also "ozone layer."

The atmospheric layer is identified as the same as the intersection of a fluid layer and something that is at least part of some atmosphere. It is also described as a type of fluid layer and a type of something that is at least part of some atmosphere, as well as a type of something that is at least composed primarily of some gaseous environmental material. Moreover, the atmospheric layer is defined as a layer that is part of the atmosphere and has a related synonym, which is atmospheric layering.

A boundary layer is a type of fluid interface layer that serves as the bounding layer of an intersection between a material entity and a part of some environmental system. It is also adjacent to a surface layer. The definition of a boundary layer is a layer of fluid in the immediate vicinity of a bounding surface, where the effects of viscosity are significant enough to distort the surrounding non-viscous flow. Additionally, "boundary layer" is an exact synonym for itself.

The ionosphere is a type of atmospheric layer that is part of the Earth's atmosphere extending from about 60 to 1,000 kilometers above the planetary surface. It is ionized by solar radiation and encompasses the thermosphere as well as parts of the mesosphere and exosphere. Furthermore, the term "ionosphere" is also used as a synonym for itself, highlighting its unique characteristics and importance.

The exosphere is a type of atmospheric layer that is at least adjacent to the thermosphere. It is defined as an atmospheric layer where molecules are gravitationally bound to a planetary body, but their density is too low for them to behave as a gas by colliding with each other. In the case of bodies with substantial atmospheres, such as Earth's atmosphere, the exosphere is the uppermost layer, where the atmosphere thins out and merges with interplanetary space, located directly above the thermosphere.

A glaze ice layer is a type of water ice layer and also a type of something that at least formed as a result of some freezing rainfall. It is defined as a smooth, transparent, and homogeneous ice layer which coats some surface and which is formed when freezing rain or drizzle hits that surface. Moreover, "glaze" is both a broad and related synonym for glaze ice layer, with "glaze ice" also being a related synonym.

A eutrophic lake is a type of lake that is defined as a lake which has nutrient-rich water. It is equivalent to something that is both a lake and at least composed primarily of eutrophic water. This indicates that a eutrophic lake is characterized by being composed primarily of eutrophic water.
